        "title": "What is this method returning?",
        "body": "<p>What does the \"(int)\" actually do in the following return statement?         <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public double calc(double amount){\n    return (int)(amount * 100)/100;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I was expecting that this method would return the same value that was passed in since I'm multiplying by 100 and then dividing by 100 . . . bringing me back to the original value yet when I tested in the compiler that was false. For Instance: <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>    carInformation myCar = new carInformation(\"\");\n    System.out.println(myCar.calc(34.86432456789));\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I get:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>34.0\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>why is this so?<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 19233298,
