    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/dJrV3.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 1888343,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1707091,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1707091/rgettman",
                "reputation": 178723,
                "display_name": "rgettman"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1381175327,
            "creation_date": 1381175327,
            "body": "<p>After the multiplication, the cast to <code>int<\/code> truncates anything beyond the decimal point, so\n<code>3486.432456789<\/code> becomes <code>3486<\/code>, which is divided by 100 to get <code>34<\/code>.  It's overkill; no multiplication or division was necessary, just: <code>(int) amount<\/code>.  Then the return value is a <code>double<\/code>, so it gets implicitly converted back to a <code>double<\/code>: <code>34.0<\/code>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 19233362,
            "question_id": 19233298
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/CWfXh.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 211794,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 464188,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/464188/bucket",
                "reputation": 7559,
                "display_name": "Bucket",
                "accept_rate": 91
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1381175246,
            "creation_date": 1381175246,
            "body": "<p>Because it is cast to an <code>int<\/code>, it will truncate the value <code>34.86...<\/code> to <code>34<\/code>. Integers don't store decimal places, so it just chops off anything to the right of the decimal point.<\/p>\n\n<p>But since you return a <code>double<\/code>, your method converts your value and adds the extra decimal place: <code>34.0<\/code>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 19233334,
            "question_id": 19233298
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4ec21df1e55febf8deb2e3b24b9cb39b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 195331,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 438154,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/438154/sotirios-delimanolis",
                "reputation": 281049,
                "display_name": "Sotirios Delimanolis",
                "accept_rate": 98
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1381175497,
            "creation_date": 1381175497,
            "body": "<p>This is called <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-5.html#jls-5.1.3\" rel=\"nofollow\">Narrowing Primitive Conversion<\/a>. A conversion is done as described<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>In the first step, the floating-point number is converted either to a\n  long, if T is long, or to an int, if T is byte, short, char, or int,\n  as follows:<\/p>\n  \n  <p>Otherwise, if the floating-point number is not an infinity, the\n  floating-point value is rounded to an integer value V, rounding toward\n  zero using IEEE 754 round-toward-zero mode (§4.2.3). Then there are\n  two cases:<\/p>\n  \n  <p>If T is long, and this integer value can be represented as a long,\n  then the result of the first step is the long value V.<\/p>\n  \n  <p>Otherwise, if this integer value can be represented as an int, then\n  the result of the first step is the int value V.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>So the value of<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>(amount * 100)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>which is of type <code>double<\/code>, is converted to an <code>int<\/code> because of the cast. It is then divided  by <code>100<\/code>. Because your method is declared as returning a <code>double<\/code>, that result is <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-5.html#jls-5.1.2\" rel=\"nofollow\">widened<\/a> from <code>int<\/code> to <code>double<\/code> with the following rule:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>[...] the resulting floating-point value will be a correctly rounded\n  version of the integer value, using IEEE 754 round-to-nearest mode<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n",
            "answer_id": 19233419,
            "question_id": 19233298
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/00f9d78517e7e17837e0e7ac227305ca?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 51914,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 155137,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/155137/martijn-courteaux",
                "reputation": 69136,
                "display_name": "Martijn Courteaux",
                "accept_rate": 91
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1381177262,
            "creation_date": 1381177262,
            "body": "<ul>\n<li>The <code>(int)<\/code> casts the numerator to an int. So, you will have 3486.<\/li>\n<li>The <code>/100<\/code> performs an <em>integer division<\/em>. You will have 34.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>To achieve what you want, perform a floating-point division:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>return (int)(amount * 100.0) / 100.0;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 19234000,
            "question_id": 19233298
        }
    ],
